               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400302-name-319" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-319" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-319" type="surname" value="HAGGIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-319" type="given" value="JONATHAN"></interp>JONATHAN HAGGIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a fitter's labourer to Mr. Francis Bramah and his partners. The prisoner was in their employ as a bricklayer—I was at work at a club-house in St. Jamess-street, and the prisoner was employed on the same job—I was using this lead on the 11th of February, and left it in the area—I know one of these pieces of lead in particular—they are the property of my masters, and are worth about 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I had left one of them in a ladle.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184003020041"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What time did you leave it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I had done using it at one o'clock, but I saw it at four o'clock, when I left the premises—it had been there from the Saturday before—I have been three years in the prosecutors' employ—I have been in the police, but have left it nine years—I can swear to one of these pieces of lead, which has a chisel mark on it—(<hi rend="italic">examining it.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400302-name-320" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-320" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-320" type="surname" value="HUGHES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-320" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY HUGHES</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable B</hi> 145.) On the night of the 11th of February I saw the prisoner in Brewer's-green—he had a sack, which con<lb></lb>tained this lead—I asked what he had got—he said, "Some tools"—I opened the sack, and found this lead, but no tools—he told me the plumber where he had been at work, in St. James's-street, Piccadilly, gave him the pieces of lead.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
